&#xa0;
[normal]Written evidence submitted by Kensa Engineering Ltd (HOT25)[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]1.0  [bold]Why does the RHI not seem to promote heat pumps successfully[bold]?[bold]1.1 
[normal]              
[normal]Phase One of the RHI, launched in November 2011, provides support for ground source heat pum
[normal]p installations into commercial and industrial buildings as well as district heating systems in the residential sector.  It has been an unmitigated disaster for the ground source heat pump industry, a position that was made clear by Kensa and many others d
[normal]uring policy development and, especially, after the announcement of the launch tariffs in March 2011.  
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]1.2
[normal]              
[normal]Sadly, the proposed Phase Two RHI policy, announced earlier in the summer and due for launch in the Spring of 2014, is similarly afflicted with iss
[normal]ues that will conspire to have a negative impact on heat pump deployment.  That said, it is presumed that the Committee is keener to learn about the failure of Phase One hence the emphasis in this written evidence. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]1.3
[normal]              
[normal]The Phase One RHI public report, ac
[normal]cessed from Ofgem’s website on August 29
[normal]th
[normal], reveals that ground source heat pumps account for just 42 of the 1605 accredited installations; the installed capacity is a paltry 1.947MW.  By contrast, there are 1496 biomass boiler installations.  Most observe
[normal]rs believe the market split of these two technologies prior to the introduction of the RHI was broadly 50/50.  That said, precise market data relating to the relative appeal of these two technologies prior to the RHI is scarce, although a DECC report on th
[normal]e Low Carbon Buildings Programme (Phase 2), a scheme which provided a capital grant for select applications including schools and community buildings, makes clear that ground source heat pumps were seemingly more popular than biomass boilers
[normal]1
[normal].   
[normal]1.4
[normal]              
[normal]Given
[normal] this background, the subsequent significant market distortion prompted by inadequate RHI policy is entirely the fault of ignorant civil servants.  For sure, officials have failed to understand basic commercial issues (see below).  In addition, there has b
[normal]een a failure to properly audit the quality of information provided by third party consultants.  These shortcomings prompted Kensa Engineering to file an official complaint with DECC in early 2013.
[normal]1.5
[normal]              
[normal]According to DECC, the intent of Phase One of the RHI 
[normal]was to provide a 12% rate of return to encourage the replacement of fossil fuel boilers.  The tariff calculation methodology was based upon very flawed logic.  Bizarrely, higher tariffs are offered for less efficient technologies on the basis that the runn
[normal]ing 
[normal]cost savings will be more modest; as a consequence, it is argued that more public subsidy will be required to deliver the required rate of return.  
[normal]Clearly, this is nonsense.  However, it gets worse.  
[normal]1.6
[normal]              
[normal]DECC presumes that the two benefits – the RHI
[normal] income and the running cost savings – accrue to the same entity and that entity is responsible for the capital investment in the renewable heat installation.  This is patently not the case whenever there is a landlord/tenant relationship, common-place at 
[normal]the commercial and industrial properties served by Phase One, or whenever a funder has financed the installation cost.  In these cases, the landlord/funder receives the RHI income and the tenant merely benefits from any running cost savings.  As a conseque
[normal]nce, there is a clear motivation for the landlord (or funder) to select the technology that has a relatively low capital cost and a high running cost
[normal]2
[normal]. This reality has prompted the sudden popularity of biomass boilers in this sector.  
[normal]This issue persists
[normal] to this day and is a fundamental flaw with the RHI.  
[normal]1.7
[normal]              
[normal]DECC is trying to remedy other issues but progress is painfully slow and, typical to the whole RHI programme, often delivered months behind its own chosen schedule.  As one example, in April 2012, 
[normal]Kensa provided DECC with compelling evidence that the launch GSHP tariffs were woefully inadequate if the intent was to deliver a 12% rate of return.  Already, there was significant market evidence to support this view as deployment levels were tiny and mo
[normal]st of the accredited installations had fortuitously qualified for the RHI (by virtue of being installed after July 2009): they certainly hadn’t been incentivised by it; nobody was interested.  The GSHPA supported Kensa’s position and expressed its concern 
[normal]in letters to the Minister, Gregory Barker MP.  
[normal]1.8
[normal]              
[normal]In response, DECC chose to employ Sweetts
[normal] Group to SEEK further evidence to establish whether the tariffs required revision. Sadly, their report was commissioned late, and delivered late, before a consultation was belatedly staged.  A final decision (about increasing the tariffs) is expected in t
[normal]he Autumn of 2013.  The proposed tariffs outlined in the consultation match the levels suggested by Kensa; they are around 2.5 times higher than the present tariffs, a margin of error which highlights the ineptitude of the original work (performed by AEA a
[normal]nd endorsed by a supposed ‘expert panel’ at DECC).  Nobody at DECC has ever revealed who sat on this ‘expert panel’; it probably didn’t exist.
[normal]1.9
[normal]              
[normal]This endorsement really was astonishingly incompetent and bordering on negligent.  For example, DECC had assu
[normal]med that the load factor for a typical heat pump installation (in heating only mode) was 35% (ie. it operated for over one third of the year).  As a consequence, it was presumed the annual running cost savings would be substantial which, as we have seen, r
[normal]educes the tariff.  In reality, any heating industry professional would have pointed out typical load factors were closer to 20% and lower for buildings without seven day occupation.  We have already established that no landlord or funder has any interest 
[normal]in a technology with a lower tariff caused by its exceptional efficiency and minimal running costs!
[normal]1.10
[normal]              
[normal]But perhaps most worryingly of all, the ‘best practice’ application of ground source heat pumps, the ability to provide both heating and cooling, was e
[normal]xcluded from RHI eligibility thanks to DECC’s initial insistence that only applications featuring ‘naturally occurring’ heat could qualify.  Installations which cooled the building during summer and re-charged (re-heated) the ground using the waste heat we
[normal]re disqualified.  Nobody within the GSHP industry had any inkling that this decision would be taken; indeed, the vast majority of the evidence 
[normal]provided prior to launch was linked to heating and cooling applications because they were the very installations 
[normal]that made financial sense and represented the majority of all prior installations.  This versatility is the true strength of the technology in the commercial sector.  
[normal]1.11
[normal]              
[normal]Again, DECC is very slowly working towards a solution; meantime, the GSHP industry 
[normal]has been virtually destroyed.  Any solutions which enhance the appeal of GSHP’s will take time to have a commercial impact on the surviving companies so further casualties are likely which could delay or eliminate any recovery in deployment levels.  All th
[normal]is could have been avoided if DECC had employed some scientists and engineers during the initial policy development rather than rely on the shoddy work of consultants and its own economists.  In Kensa’s opinion, the Select Committee should satisfy itself t
[normal]hat the senior responsible civil servant is competent enough to deliver future RHI policy without industry having to suffer the consequences of further avoidable errors.
[normal]--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
[normal]------------------------------------------------
[normal]1
[normal] DECC Low Carbon Building Programme, 2006-2011, Final Report (August 2011)
[normal]This report does not specifically detail the number of installations featuring each eligible technology; instead, it highlights the
[normal] level of financial support provided to each technology, split by the type of applicant (see Table below).  The capital grant percentages were consistent between GSHP and biomass boilers.  The ‘School’ line provides the best comparison.  Even allowing for 
[normal]the higher cost of GSHP installations, it is clear that the significantly higher total grant spend demonstrates that GSHP’s were the more popular technology prior to the launch of the RHI, within schools, at least.  Kensa has not spoken to a school about a
[normal] GSHP installation since the RHI was launched in 2011.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]2
