[normal]DECC Fossil Fuel Price Projections
[normal] - October 2012
[normal]Thermal storage is a potential useful method of balancing electricity/energy demand both diurnally [bold]and annually.[bold]&#xa0;[bold] What is government policy doing to promote thermal storage, and should it do more/different?[bold]There is a real opportunity for Government to recognise that ground source heat pumps can contribute significantly in this area.  In its 4
[normal]th
[normal] Carbon 
[normal]budget, the Committee for Climate Change has indicated that 6.8m heat pumps will be installed by 2030.  Given this number, it is vital that 
[normal]very careful consideration is given to the relative efficiency of the various heat pump types.  Most studies, 
[normal]including the latest EST Heat Pump Field Trial (Getting Warmer: July 2013) report that GSHP’s are at least 15% more efficient but this base superior efficiency can be further enhanced by inter-seasonal heat transfer and the utilisation of any waste heat to
[normal] bolster ground temperatures.
[normal]But there is a much bigger advantage if ground source heat pumps are favoured.  S
[normal]pare grid capacity will exist through the night so heat pump installations should be
[normal] over-sized and
[normal] designed to operate at this time
[normal] with the hea
[normal]t stored in some fashion (see below) for subsequent use during the day
[normal].  This requirement creates difficulties for air source heat pumps because the air temperature is typically around 6
[normal]o
[normal]C
[normal] cooler at 2am rather than 2pm which means the appliance is 
[normal]signific
[normal]antly 
[normal]less efficient.  Worse, most people are trying to 
[normal]sleep at 2am 
[normal]so the n
[normal]oise nuisance of many 
[normal]ASHP’s 
[normal]operating at this time 
[normal]is considerable.  By contrast, neither of these two drawbacks 
[normal]will 
[normal]occur if
[normal] ground source heat pumps are favoured.
[normal]Of course, t
[normal]here needs to be more research into the right medium for storing the heat generated during the night.  This could be performed using large volumes of water but this is usually impractical; it could be performed by storing heat in the building structure but
[normal] this may not be sufficiently controllable; instead, the most exciting current opportunity is phase change materials and more research is required in this area.
[normal]There are some very interesting opportunities but the blinkered approach of the RHI is not help
[normal]ful.  The RHI is looking to deliver renewable heat cheaply to achieve the 2020 target: it certainly doesn’t lay the proper foundations for the achievement of the more important, and more challenging, longer-term carbon emission reduction targets.  DECC’s f
[normal]ailure to use the RHI to support the wider heat strategy is a further indictment on this abject policy.
[normal]September 2013
